.TH "HTMLElement.offsetWidth" "JS" "July 26, 2024" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
HTMLElement.offsetWidth \- HTMLElement: offsetWidth property
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]HTMLElement.offsetWidth\f[B]\f[R] read\-only property
returns the layout width of an element as an integer.
.PP
Typically, \f[CR]offsetWidth\f[R] is a measurement in pixels of the
element\[cq]s CSS width, including any borders, padding, and vertical
scrollbars (if rendered).
It does not include the width of pseudo\-elements such as
\f[CR]::before\f[R] or \f[CR]::after\f[R].
.PP
If the element is hidden (for example, by setting
\f[CR]style.display\f[R] on the element or one of its ancestors to
\f[CR]\[dq]none\[dq]\f[R]), then \f[CR]0\f[R] is returned.
.SH VALUE
An integer corresponding to the \f[CR]offsetWidth\f[R] pixel value of
the element.
The \f[CR]offsetWidth\f[R] property is a read\-only.
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Note:\f[R] This property will round the value to an integer.
If you need a fractional value, use
\f[CR]element.getBoundingClientRect()\f[R].
.RE
